author: Staff reports
title: College rewind: No. 13 Hope volleyball upsets No. 11 Carthage
text: Posted Oct. 16, 2015 at 11:59 PM Updated at 11:59 PM Posted Oct. 16, 2015 at 11:59 PM Holland, Mich. The 13th-ranked Hope College volleyball team opened the 2015 Midwest Invitational with wins against 11th-ranked Carthage and Bluffton on Friday. The Flying Dutch improved to 16-5 overall. Haley Muller totaled a match-high 11 kills during a 25-18, 25-17, 25-20 decision over Carthage (20-5). Sarah Feldpausch chipped in nine kills. Lauren Hazekamp collected 36 assists. Muller netted 10 kills during a 25-12, 25-13, 23-25, 25-12 decision against Bluffton (14-8). Feldpausch and Courtney Van Houzen each had 11 kills. Vanessa Reynhout and Katie Rietberg (West Ottawa) added 10 kills apiece. GVSU splits at tourney For the second time in the day, the No. 23 Grand Valley State volleyball team went the maximum five sets in its contests at the Midwest Region Crossover Tournament, but unlike their morning result, the Lakers were able to overcome Indianapolis to capture the strong 3-2 victory (15-25, 25-16, 25-23, 21-25, 16-14) in Aurora, Ill. GVSU dropped a five-set final to No. 19 Lewis in the early afternoon, with the Flyers taking control late in set five to claim the 15-11 win. The Lakers flipped the script in the late moments against Indianapolis, as Jessica Majerle tallied a solo block and a kill, followed by a combined block between Shannon Winicki and Staci Brower to seal the victory. Cross Country Hope runs at MCC Invit e Claire Cooper posted a 5K time of 19 minutes, 50 seconds to lead the Hope College womenâ€™s cross country team at the Muskegon Community College Invitational on Friday. The Flying Dutch finished fourth at the invitational at University Park Golf Course, while the men were ninth. Kate Kooiker (Hamilton) followed Cooper (20:20.00). Finishing behind Kooiker was Ellie Best (20:32.00), Mackenzie Govier (20:34.00) and Kelly Ocock (20:38.00). Nicholas Salomon (27:27.00) led the men, followed by Austin Elluru (27:50.00), Frank Moen (28:00.00), Noah Litwiller (28:13.00) and William Henkel (28:35.00). By Staff reports
